1. Focus Mode (Zen Mode)
What it is: A toggle button that dims or fades out the rest of the UI (navigation, sidebars, breadcrumbs) and leaves only the current paragraph and diagram visible in the center of the screen.
Why it's great: It completely eliminates distractions, allowing the student to hyper-focus on the exact sentence being highlighted and spoken.
2. Audio Playback Controls (Speed & Navigation)
What it is: Adding a sleek mini-player that lets the user:
Change the narrator's speed (0.75x, 1x, 1.25x, 1.5x) so fast learners can speed it up, and those who need more time can slow it down.
Click "Previous Concept" or "Next Concept" to jump around the audio, instead of having to listen strictly linearly.
3. Micro-Knowledge Checks (Interactive Pauses)
What it is: After a complex concept or at the end of a section, the audio pauses automatically. A small, beautiful interactive pop-up appears with a single multiple-choice question (e.g., "Quick check: What is the main job of the CPU?").
Why it's great: Active learning! It forces the user to stop passively listening and prove they understood the concept before the audio continues.
4. Progress Memory (Resume where you left off)
What it is: If a user is listening to an explanation, gets halfway through, and closes the app, the next time they open that unit, it asks: "Resume listening from Concept 3?"
Why it's great: It creates a seamless, app-like experience that respects the user's time.
5. Subtle Audio Visualizer
What it is: A tiny, elegant animated waveform (like a Siri or Google Assistant glow) that pulses near the play button or at the bottom of the screen while the narrator is speaking.
Why it's great: It adds a premium, "alive" micro-interaction that visually reinforces that the app is actively "talking" to them.
